//axhob_operation
{rbtgo_ark_enshrine}

NOTE: This operation enshrines upstream base images into
{gar_service}
as content-addressed, human-readable anchors.
The
{rbtr_director}
submits a Cloud Build job that copies each declared
{rbrv_image_origin}
from its upstream registry to GAR with an anchor tag using
the reliquary skopeo image
(`skopeo copy --all`), preserving the manifest list and all per-platform manifests for multi-platform images.
The anchor results are returned via `buildStepOutputs` and
{rbrv_image_anchor}
is then written back to the vessel regime locally.

NOTE: Enshrine is a pre-build preparation step.
It must be run before
{rbtgo_ark_conjure}
when anchored base images are desired.
Conjure works without anchors (passing ORIGIN through), but anchored images provide reproducibility and air-gap readiness.

NOTE: Enshrine runs on Cloud Build, not the Director's workstation.
No local skopeo installation is required.
The GCB step uses Mason SA ambient credentials via the metadata server for GAR writes.

The enshrine operation:

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{rbrv_sigil}
. *Validate Input Parameters*:
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel provided as first argument
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel contains at least one
{rbrv_image_origin}
declaration (slots 1-3)
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel mode is `conjure` (`RBRV_VESSEL_MODE`)
.. {rbbc_require}
reliquary tool images exist in GAR (HEAD check on `docker:latest` canary)

//axhos_step
. *Submit Enshrine Cloud Build Job*:
.. Compose `builds.create` JSON with:
... Single step using
the reliquary skopeo image
as the builder image (script: `rbgje01-enshrine-copy.sh`)
... `_RBGE_*` substitutions: `_RBGE_GAR_HOST`, `_RBGE_GAR_PATH`, `_RBGE_IMAGE_n_ORIGIN` (n = 1, 2, 3; empty for unused slots). Base images are stored in the shared `enshrines/` namespace, with each anchor as a peer package (`«PREFIX»enshrines/«ANCHOR»:«ANCHOR»`), not per-vessel.
... Mason SA, private pool, timeout
.. Submit via `builds.create` and wait for completion
.. The GCB step, for each non-empty ORIGIN slot:
... Fetches the raw upstream manifest (`skopeo inspect --raw`) and computes its sha256 digest (`sha256sum` of the raw manifest bytes)
... {rbbc_store}
`<<DIGEST>>` -- the sha256 digest of the upstream manifest (manifest list digest for multi-platform images, single manifest digest for single-platform images)
... Constructs anchor: sanitize full origin string (`:` `/` replaced with `-`), append first 10 hex chars of sha256 digest
... Example: `python:3.11-slim` with `sha256:abc123def4...` produces `python-3.11-slim-abc123def4`
... Copies upstream image into the shared `enshrines/` namespace in GAR as a peer package at `«PREFIX»enshrines/«ANCHOR»:«ANCHOR»` using `skopeo copy --all`, transferring the manifest list and all per-platform manifests atomically. Each anchor is its own package under the namespace — the path segment carries the anchor identity, and the tag redundantly restates it so divergence is a visible bug. The anchor is vessel-independent — multiple vessels sharing the same base image origin share one enshrined package.
... {rbbc_require}
copy succeeds -- the anchor tag is now a permanent, content-addressed reference in
{gar_service}
containing all upstream platforms
... Single-platform upstream images are handled identically -- `skopeo copy --all` is a no-op on the platform dimension when only one platform exists
.. Writes JSON anchor results to `/builder/outputs/output` (returned as `buildStepOutputs`)

//axhos_step
. *Extract Anchors and Write Regime*:
.. Read `buildStepOutputs[0]` from the completed build result (base64-decoded JSON)
.. For each slot present in the result:
... Write anchor string to `RBRV_IMAGE_n_ANCHOR` in the vessel's `rbrv.env`

//axhoot_typed_output
{rbrv_image_anchor}
Per-slot anchor string written to the vessel regime.

//axhoc_completion
Successful execution produces anchored base image references in
{gar_service}
(with all upstream platforms preserved) and updates the vessel regime with
{rbrv_image_anchor}
values.
The vessel is now ready for reproducible
{rbtgo_ark_conjure}
builds using GAR-mirrored base images.
Multi-platform conjure vessels pull the correct platform from the anchored manifest list automatically.
Re-running enshrine with the same
{rbrv_image_origin}
but a different upstream digest produces a new anchor (upstream image was updated).
Re-running with the same digest is idempotent.

is minted locally by the
{rbtr_director}
before submission.
The Director knows the complete artifact tag set before the build begins -- naming authority and verification authority are the same entity.

NOTE: The conjure build job runs on the worker pool selected by the vessel's `RBRV_EGRESS_MODE`: tether pool for vessels needing public internet (e.g., `apt-get` in Dockerfile), airgap pool for vessels with all dependencies enshrined in GAR.
The subsequent {rbtgo_ark_vouch} always runs on the airgap pool regardless of vessel egress mode.

The conjure operation:

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{rbtga_ark}
. *Validate Input Parameters*:
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel provided as first argument
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel contains conjuring configuration (RBRV_CONJURE_DOCKERFILE, RBRV_CONJURE_BLDCONTEXT)

//axhos_step
. *Registry Preflight*:
.. *Reliquary check*: HEAD request to `«RELIQUARY»/docker:latest` manifest in
{gar_service}.
{rbbc_require}
HTTP 200 — on 404, fail with directive to run inscribe first.
The reliquary is a co-versioned set of builder tool images inscribed from upstream into private GAR. Each vessel declares its reliquary; multiple datestamped reliquaries can coexist.
.. *Enshrine check*: For each indexed slot (n = 1, 2, 3) where both
{rbrv_image_origin}
and
{rbrv_image_anchor}
are set:
... HEAD request to `«PREFIX»enshrines/«ANCHOR»:«ANCHOR»` manifest in
{gar_service}
... {rbbc_require}
HTTP 200 — on 404, fail with directive to run {rbtgo_ark_enshrine} first.
Multiple vessels sharing the same anchor need only one enshrine.
